{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493235","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493235"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:01:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:01:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1260"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1260","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1260"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.2,0.52,0.08,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1260"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106402"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1260","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1260"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1260"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88855"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"414"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5364"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2761"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11884"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16198"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37697"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43839"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44981"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106402"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 18-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic concerned about his risk of developing cancer. He is otherwise well and has no symptoms. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His father was diagnosed with colorectal cancer at the age of 54 years following a positive faecal occult blood test. His 45-year-old paternal uncle was found to have several polyps on colonoscopy. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate colorectal cancer screening regimen for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Five-yearly colonoscopy starting now","Biennial faecal occult blood testing starting at age 45","Five-yearly colonoscopy starting at age 44","Five-yearly colonoscopy starting at age 50","Referral to a familial cancer service"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is at moderate increased risk (Category 2) of developing colorectal cancer (CRC) due to having one first-degree relative (his father) diagnosed with CRC under the age of 60. This places him at a 2-4 times increased risk compared to the general population. A family history of colorectal polyps is not considered an additional risk factor, unless there is concern for a hereditary polyposis syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate screening regimen for this patient is \u003Cstrong\u003Efive-yearly colonoscopy starting at age 44\u003C/strong\u003E. This is because colonoscopy screening should begin 10 years before the age at which the first-degree relative was diagnosed (54 years in this case) or at age 50, whichever comes first. He would also be recommended to do faecal occult blood testing. For the average risk patient, this could commence at the age of 45 and for those in higher risk groups, it could be started earlier.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFive-yearly colonoscopy starting now\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as the patient is only 18 years old, which is far too early to begin screening even in moderate-risk individuals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBiennial faecal occult blood testing starting at age 45\u003C/strong\u003E is the recommended screening regimen for average-risk individuals, not those at moderate increased risk like this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFive-yearly colonoscopy starting at age 50\u003C/strong\u003E would be too late for this patient, given his father\u0027s diagnosis at age 54.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral to a familial cancer service\u003C/strong\u003E is typically reserved for high-risk individuals, such as those with multiple affected relatives or known genetic syndromes. This patient\u0027s family history does not meet these criteria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECurrent colorectal cancer risk categories based on family history and screening recommendations are as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECategory 1 - similar risk as the general population\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsymptomatic people with no family history of colorectal cancer OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOne 1st-degree relative with CRC \u226560 years\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreening\u003C/strong\u003E: FOBT should be completed every 2 years from 45 years old as per usual screening protocol. Colonoscopy is generally not recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECategory 2 - moderately increased risk\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsymptomatic people with one 1st-degree relative CRC diagnosed \u0026lt;60 years OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwo 1st-degree relatives with CRC at any age or one 1st-degree and one or more 2nd-degree relatives diagnosed at any age\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreening\u003C/strong\u003E: Colonoscopy should be offered 5 yearly starting at 10 years younger than the earliest diagnosis of CRC in a 1st-degree relative, or age 50 (whichever is earliest), to age 74 years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECategory 3 - high risk\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsymptomatic with two 1st-degree and one 2nd-degree relative with colorectal cancer, with at least one diagnosed before 50 years old OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwo 1st-degree relatives and two or more 2nd-degree relatives diagnosed with CRC at any age OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThree or more 1st-degree relatives with CRC at any age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreening\u003C/strong\u003E: refer to the familial cancer clinic for genetic assessment before a screening decision is made if Lynch syndrome has not been excluded. If Lynch syndrome is excluded, colonoscopy should be offered every 5 years starting at 10 years younger than the earliest age of diagnosis of colorectal cancer in a first-degree relative or age 40 years (whichever is earlier), to age 74 years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELow dose aspirin has been found to reduce the risk of developing colorectal cancer and may be considered from age 45-70 as primary prevention, particularly in higher risk groups.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Individuals with one first-degree relative diagnosed with colorectal cancer under 60 years of age are at moderate increased risk and should begin colonoscopy screening at age 50 or 10 years younger than the earliest diagnosis, whichever comes first.","Moderate increased risk of colorectal cancer warrants colonoscopy every 5 years, not faecal occult blood testing.","Referral to a familial cancer service is reserved for those at high risk, typically with multiple affected relatives or known genetic syndromes."],"references":["RACGP. Guidance for preventative activities in general practice: colorectal cancer. 2024. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/preventive-activities-in-general-practice/cancer/colorectal-cancer","Cancer Council Australia. Clinical practice guidelines for the prevention, early detection and management of colorectal cancer: Risk and screening based on family history. 2024. Available at: https://app.magicapp.org/#/guideline/jz5DdE"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88855"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1260"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88855","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88855"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-19T16:20:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-19T16:22:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1260"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106402"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemC